voice_to_text: Uh, boys and girls are different. My daughter is beach water. Every day different. Some days calm and clear, some days churning, boiling, crashing. The only constant for a girl is change. The tides pulling her in directions she never chose. Everyone judges the beach against their expectations. Too rough, too calm, too cold. Not what they wanted. Today everyone needs something from the water. Comfort, beauty, peace. But no one asks what the beach needs. Her mother, she's the ocean water. She knows those shallow tides because she lived em. But now she faces currents our daughter can't even see yet. Storms that would terrify the beach. Still, she is expected to be beautiful, bountiful, providing everything without receiving. Sometimes they clash. Beach meeting ocean creates massive riptides. Mother and daughter, both water pulling in different directions, both changing, both under pressure, both exhausted from being everything to everyone. And me, I'm the harbour wall. I don't understand water. I'm stoned. I can't feel the tides. I can't change with the currents. I don't know what it's like to be pulled by the moon. To change without choosing, to be needed by everyone while drowning. But I don't need to understand. I need to be the one thing that doesn't change. The fixed point they can crash against without breaking me. The shelter that's always there. No matter how far they sail or how wild the storm. When my daughter storms against me, I absorb it. When my wife's Ocean rage needs somewhere to break. She can flood into my harbor, and my depths can absorb the chaos, returning it to stillness. Not with solutions. With unshakeable presence. I'm not trying to control the water. I'm giving it a container of safety if they need it. They don't need me to become water, too. They need me to be the harbour. Fast, immovable, always there. That's what fathers and husbands are for. To be the one unchanging thing in a world of constant change.

Parents went to Grandma's 90th birthday two hours away, and I told them I could handle it because I've done it 100 times before. The storm hit harder than expected, and the power went out around six PM, but Danny had already done his evening nebulizer, so we just lit some candles and played cards and listened to the ice hitting the windows. Around eight PM, he started coughing more than usual. I did chest percussion like they taught me, pounding on his back to loosen everything up, and he coughed a bunch of stuff up and seemed better. By nine PM, the coughing was worse, deep and wet, and Danny said his chest felt tight. I gave him his rescue inhaler, two puffs like the doctor showed us, and waited. He still couldn't catch his breath between coughing fits. I tried to call our parents, but my cell was dead. Towers overloaded from the storm. I tried 9 1 1 and got nothing but static. The landline was out because ice took Down the lines, Danny. His breathing was getting faster and shallower and his nostrils were flaring with each breath. I recognised this from hospital trips. Respiratory distress. I did more chest therapy and tried the inhaler again and nothing worked. Danny's lips were turning blue at the edges. He was using muscles in his neck and stomach just to breathe. His whole body working for every bit of air. He looked at me with scared eyes and said, I can't get air. I tried every phone again and got nothing. I ran outside and banged on neighbour's doors, but no one was home or they couldn't help. Around eight PM, he started coughing more than usual. I did chest percussion like they taught me, pounding on his back to loosen everything up, and he coughed a bunch of stuff up and seemed better. By nine PM, the coughing was worse, deep and wet, and Danny said his chest felt tight. I gave him his rescue inhaler, two puffs like the doctor showed us, and waited. He still couldn't catch his breath between coughing fits. I tried to call our parents, but my cell was dead. Towers overloaded from the storm. I tried 9 1 1 and got nothing but static. The landline was out because ice took Down the lines, Danny. His breathing was getting faster and shallower and his nostrils were flaring with each breath. I recognised this from hospital trips. Respiratory distress. I did more chest therapy and tried the inhaler again and nothing worked. Danny's lips were turning blue at the edges. He was using muscles in his neck and stomach just to breathe. His whole body working for every bit of air. He looked at me with scared eyes and said, I can't get air. I tried every phone again and got nothing. I ran outside and banged on neighbour's doors, but no one was home or they couldn't help. Danny was sitting straight up because he couldn't breathe, lying down, wheezing with every exhale. His fingernails were turning blue. He was too tired to cough anymore, which was worse. My feet slipped on the icy steps and I went down hard on one knee. But I didn't drop him. The truck door was unlocked and I put Danny in the passenger seat and buckled him in. I couldn't see through the freezing rain, so I hunched over the wheel and squinted at the road. The truck slid through the first intersection and I just held on and prayed. I blew through a red light because no one else was stupid enough to be out. The truck fishtailed on the hill by the church and sideswiped a parked car. I heard metal scraping and didn't stop. The hospital was 15 minutes away. In good weather, I made it in eight. He still couldn't catch his breath between coughing fits. I tried to call our parents, but my cell was dead. Towers overloaded from the storm. I tried 9 1 1 and got nothing but static. voice_to_text: I asked to hold my baby, and the doctor told me to shut up. I've been pregnant for 41 weeks. The doctors kept saying, any day now for three weeks straight while I waddled around like a penguin. My husband works in the medical field, so I let him handle all the hospital stuff. So when he finally scheduled a date to get this baby out, I cried happy tears. My husband held my face and said, we're finally gonna meet our daughter. He's been reading parenting books. It's month two of this pregnancy, and recently took to practicing swaddling on our cat. I've never wanted anything more than to hold this baby, to finally meet the little person who's been kicking my ribs for months. The moment I walked into the section of the hospital titled Labour and delivery, something felt wrong. The intake nurse didn't even look up from her computer when I approached. Name. She snapped. I told her. She sighed like I was ruining her day. You're early. I wasn't early. I was exactly on time. She pointed down the hall. Room 4. Change into the gown on the bed. Someone will deal with you. Eventually kept telling myself it was fine, that my husband would be here soon. I texted him, just got to my room. His response made my stomach drop. Don't freak out, but I got rear ended really bad on the highway. I'm fine, but the car is totaled. Coming as fast As I can. I stared at my phone, alone in that cold room, trying not to panic. A nurse came in without knocking. She grabbed my arm and started inserting an I V. Wait, I said. My husband isn't here yet. Can we just wait until he gets here before we start anything? She didn't even look at me. We're on a schedule. I watched her push something into the line. What is that? I asked. Pitocin. But I thought we were going to discuss the plan first. She glares at me and says, you want this baby out or not? She left before I could respond. Then my husband texted me. The police are making me stay until the tow truck clears the scene. It's going to be okay, though. I love you. Within 20 minutes, my contractions started hitting hard. I was gripping the bed rails, tears streaming down my face. I pressed the call button. A different nurse appeared in the doorway. I need ice chips. I managed. Please. She glanced at her clipboard. I'll get to it. She never came back. An hour later, I pressed the button again. Another nurse. I asked for ice chips an hour ago, and I need to talk to someone about pain management. He rolled her eyes. There's water right there, and the doctor will be in when he's ready. The doctor finally appeared two hours later. He checked the monitors, checked his watch, and started toward the door. Wait. I said, crying now. I'm in so much pain. Can we please talk about an epidural or something? He barely turned around. You're only at six centimetres. This is normal. First time. Mothers always think they know better than the medical professionals. He left. I had never felt so alone. I kept texting my husband, but the last message he sent was, phone is at 1%. I will be there. You're so strong. So none of my messages were going through. The pressure became unbearable, so I screamed. The doctor rushed back in, barking orders. Nurses appeared from nowhere. Push, he commanded. But my husband. I say, I don't care. Push! I pushed until I saw stars. Until I heard a tiny cry that made everything else disappear. My husband burst through the door, somehow looking worse than me. His shirt was torn. Face panicked. I'm here! I'm here! Our daughter was in the doctor's arms. Perfect. Screaming, alive. I reached out, exhausted, sobbing. Please, please, I whispered. Can I hold my baby? The doctor didn't look at me. We need to run tests first. Please, just for one second. He finally turned irritation all over his face. Ma'am, shut up and let us do our jobs. The room went dead silent. My husband stepped forward with a look I'd never seen before. What did you just say to my wife? The doctor straightened. Sir, you need to calm down or I will have security remove you. My husband laughed. Coldly remove me. Do you have any idea who I am? He pulled out his hospital I D. Badge. I sit on this hospital's medical board. I review misconduct cases. I decide who keeps their job here. The doctor's face went white. The nurse, who rolled her eyes, physically stepped backward. The rest of you better hope you treated my wife with more compassion than the man who told my wife to shut up after she just gave birth to our child. He looked at each person in the room. Because by Monday morning, I will have every single person who mistreated my wife suspended. The doctor placed our baby in my arms so gently, you'd think she was made of glass. The nurse, who disappeared for an hour, suddenly appeared with warm blankets, ice chips and extra pillows for me. Is there anything else you need? The nurse asked me. I looked at my husband, then at our daughter's perfect face. I told the nurse, yes, for you to get out.

I reached out, exhausted, sobbing. Please, please, I whispered. Can I hold my baby? The doctor didn't look at me. We need to run tests first. Please, just for one second. He finally turned irritation all over his face. Ma'am, shut up and let us do our jobs. The room went dead silent. My husband stepped forward with a look I'd never seen before. What did you just say to my wife? The doctor straightened. Sir, you need to calm down or I will have security remove you. My husband laughed. Coldly remove me. Do you have any idea who I am? He pulled out his hospital I D. Badge. I sit on this hospital's medical board. I review misconduct cases. I decide who keeps their job here. The doctor's face went white. The nurse, who rolled her eyes, physically stepped backward. The rest of you better hope you treated my wife with more compassion than the man who told my wife to shut up after she just gave birth to our child. He looked at each person in the room. Because by Monday morning, I will have every single person who mistreated my wife suspended. The doctor placed our baby in my arms so gently, you'd think she was made of glass. The nurse, who disappeared for an hour, suddenly appeared with warm blankets, ice chips and extra pillows for me. Is there anything else you need? The nurse asked me. I looked at my husband, then at our daughter's perfect face. I told the nurse, yes, for you to get out.

video_description: üò≠üò≠@TheJubalShowJubalinthemorningradioprogram‚ÄúBrookeandJubal‚Äù#brookeandjubal#brookandjubalinthemorning#seconddate#seconddateupdate#prank
voice_to_text: When was doing the wrong thing the right choice? I was 12 years old and home alone with my little brother during the worst ice storm in 20 years. Danny was 7 and had cystic fibrosis, been managing it his whole life. I knew the routine better than my own homework. Chest physiotherapy twice a day to loosen the mucus, nebulizer treatments morning and night, enzyme pills with every meal, and always watch for signs of infection. Parents went to Grandma's 90th birthday two hours away, and I told them I could handle it because I've done it 100 times before. The storm hit harder than expected, and the power went out around six PM, but Danny had already done his evening nebulizer, so we just lit some candles and played cards and listened to the ice hitting the windows. Around eight PM, he started coughing more than usual. I did chest percussion like they taught me, pounding on his back to loosen everything up, and he coughed a bunch of stuff up and seemed better. By nine PM, the coughing was worse, deep and wet, and Danny said his chest felt tight. I gave him his rescue inhaler, two puffs like the doctor showed us, and waited. He still couldn't catch his breath between coughing fits. I tried to call our parents, but my cell was dead. Towers overloaded from the storm. I tried 9 1 1 and got nothing but static. The landline was out because ice took Down the lines, Danny. His breathing was getting faster and shallower and his nostrils were flaring with each breath. I recognised this from hospital trips. Respiratory distress. I did more chest therapy and tried the inhaler again and nothing worked. Danny's lips were turning blue at the edges. He was using muscles in his neck and stomach just to breathe. His whole body working for every bit of air. He looked at me with scared eyes and said, I can't get air. I tried every phone again and got nothing. I ran outside and banged on neighbour's doors, but no one was home or they couldn't help. Danny was sitting straight up because he couldn't breathe, lying down, wheezing with every exhale. His fingernails were turning blue. He was too tired to cough anymore, which was worse. He said, am I gonna die? And I told him no, I wasn't going to let that happen. I looked out the window at Mister Leroy's truck with chains on the tires just sitting in his driveway. Mister Leroy was at his daughter's house riding out the storm. I wrapped Danny in a blanket and carried him outside. He weighed almost nothing because C F. Always kept him small. My feet slipped on the icy steps and I went down hard on one knee. But I didn't drop him. The truck door was unlocked and I put Danny in the passenger seat and buckled him in. His head lolled to the side and The whistling sound he made with each breath was get and quieter. Keys in the visor, like always. I'd never driven, but I'd watched my parents a thousand times. I turned the key and stalled. It started again. Stalled again. Third time. I gave it more gas and the truck lurched backward and I slammed the brakes and we skidded sideways across the driveway. I got it into drive and the back end fishtailed so hard I thought we were going in the ditch. Truck shot forward, tyres spinning on ice before they caught. I couldn't see through the freezing rain, so I hunched over the wheel and squinted at the road. The truck slid through the first intersection and I just held on and prayed. Danny's breathing was barely audible now. I pushed the gas harder. We hit black ice on Miller Road and spun completely around. I was screaming as the world whipped past the windows, headlights swinging across trees and mailboxes. When we stopped, we were somehow still on the road, facing the right direction. I kept driving. I blew through a red light because no one else was stupid enough to be out. The truck fishtailed on the hill by the church and sideswiped a parked car. I heard metal scraping and didn't stop. The hospital was 15 minutes away. In good weather, I made it in eight. I pulled up to the emergency entrance going way too fast and slammed the brakes and the truck Jumped a curb and stopped half on the sidewalk. I laid on the horn until people came running. I was screaming that my brother had C F. And couldn't breathe. They put him on a stretcher, and someone put an oxygen mask on his face, and they ran him inside. A nurse found me on the waiting room floor in wet pajamas, no shoes, shaking so hard my teeth were chattering. She brought me a blanket and told me I did good. My parents arrived three hours later, hysterical. The doctor said Danny was stable. His oxygen levels were when he came in. And another hour could have caused organ damage or worse. A cop showed up the next day. About the stolen truck and the car I hit. I told him everything. Mister Leroy visited Danny in the hospital and heard the whole story. He shook my hand and told the cop there was nothing to press charges for. He said, that's not stealing. That's being a brother. Danny's 20 now and doing fine. Mister Leroy taught me to drive for real the summer I turned 15.

video_description: üò≠üò≠@TheJubalShowJubalinthemorningradioprogram‚ÄúBrookeandJubal‚Äù#brookeandjubal#brookandjubalinthemorning#seconddate#seconddateupdate#prank
voice_to_text: I asked to hold my baby, and the doctor told me to shut up. I've been pregnant for 41 weeks. The doctors kept saying, any day now for three weeks straight while I waddled around like a penguin. My husband works in the medical field, so I let him handle all the hospital stuff. So when he finally scheduled a date to get this baby out, I cried happy tears. My husband held my face and said, we're finally gonna meet our daughter. He's been reading parenting books. It's month two of this pregnancy, and recently took to practicing swaddling on our cat. I've never wanted anything more than to hold this baby, to finally meet the little person who's been kicking my ribs for months. The moment I walked into the section of the hospital titled Labour and delivery, something felt wrong. The intake nurse didn't even look up from her computer when I approached. Name. She snapped. I told her. She sighed like I was ruining her day. You're early. I wasn't early. I was exactly on time. She pointed down the hall. Room 4. Change into the gown on the bed. Someone will deal with you. Eventually kept telling myself it was fine, that my husband would be here soon. I texted him, just got to my room. His response made my stomach drop. Don't freak out, but I got rear ended really bad on the highway. I'm fine, but the car is totaled. Coming as fast As I can. I stared at my phone, alone in that cold room, trying not to panic. A nurse came in without knocking. She grabbed my arm and started inserting an I V. Wait, I said. My husband isn't here yet. Can we just wait until he gets here before we start anything? She didn't even look at me. We're on a schedule. I watched her push something into the line. What is that? I asked. Pitocin. But I thought we were going to discuss the plan first. She glares at me and says, you want this baby out or not? She left before I could respond. Then my husband texted me. The police are making me stay until the tow truck clears the scene. It's going to be okay, though. I love you. Within 20 minutes, my contractions started hitting hard. I was gripping the bed rails, tears streaming down my face. I pressed the call button. A different nurse appeared in the doorway. I need ice chips. I managed. Please. She glanced at her clipboard. I'll get to it. She never came back. An hour later, I pressed the button again. Another nurse. I asked for ice chips an hour ago, and I need to talk to someone about pain management. He rolled her eyes. There's water right there, and the doctor will be in when he's ready. The doctor finally appeared two hours later. He checked the monitors, checked his watch, and started toward the door. Wait. I said, crying now. I'm in so much pain. Can we please talk about an epidural or something? He barely turned around. You're only at six centimetres. This is normal. First time. Mothers always think they know better than the medical professionals. He left. I had never felt so alone. I kept texting my husband, but the last message he sent was, phone is at 1%. I will be there. You're so strong. So none of my messages were going through. The pressure became unbearable, so I screamed. The doctor rushed back in, barking orders. Nurses appeared from nowhere. Push, he commanded. But my husband. I say, I don't care. Push! I pushed until I saw stars. Until I heard a tiny cry that made everything else disappear. My husband burst through the door, somehow looking worse than me. His shirt was torn. Face panicked. I'm here! I'm here! Our daughter was in the doctor's arms. Perfect. Screaming, alive. I reached out, exhausted, sobbing. Please, please, I whispered. Can I hold my baby? The doctor didn't look at me. We need to run tests first. Please, just for one second. He finally turned irritation all over his face. Ma'am, shut up and let us do our jobs. The room went dead silent. My husband stepped forward with a look I'd never seen before. What did you just say to my wife? The doctor straightened. Sir, you need to calm down or I will have security remove you. My husband laughed. Coldly remove me. Do you have any idea who I am? He pulled out his hospital I D. Badge. I sit on this hospital's medical board. I review misconduct cases. I decide who keeps their job here. The doctor's face went white. The nurse, who rolled her eyes, physically stepped backward. The rest of you better hope you treated my wife with more compassion than the man who told my wife to shut up after she just gave birth to our child. He looked at each person in the room. Because by Monday morning, I will have every single person who mistreated my wife suspended. The doctor placed our baby in my arms so gently, you'd think she was made of glass. The nurse, who disappeared for an hour, suddenly appeared with warm blankets, ice chips and extra pillows for me. Is there anything else you need? The nurse asked me. I looked at my husband, then at our daughter's perfect face. I told the nurse, yes, for you to get out.

video_description: üò≠üò≠@TheJubalShowJubalinthemorningradioprogram‚ÄúBrookeandJubal‚Äù#brookeandjubal#brookandjubalinthemorning#seconddate#seconddateupdate#prank
voice_to_text: When was doing the wrong thing the right choice? I was 12 years old and home alone with my little brother during the worst ice storm in 20 years. Danny was 7 and had cystic fibrosis, been managing it his whole life. I knew the routine better than my own homework. Chest physiotherapy twice a day to loosen the mucus, nebulizer treatments morning and night, enzyme pills with every meal, and always watch for signs of infection. Parents went to Grandma's 90th birthday two hours away, and I told them I could handle it because I've done it 100 times before. The storm hit harder than expected, and the power went out around six PM, but Danny had already done his evening nebulizer, so we just lit some candles and played cards and listened to the ice hitting the windows. Around eight PM, he started coughing more than usual. I did chest percussion like they taught me, pounding on his back to loosen everything up, and he coughed a bunch of stuff up and seemed better. By nine PM, the coughing was worse, deep and wet, and Danny said his chest felt tight. I gave him his rescue inhaler, two puffs like the doctor showed us, and waited. He still couldn't catch his breath between coughing fits. I tried to call our parents, but my cell was dead. Towers overloaded from the storm. I tried 9 1 1 and got nothing but static. The landline was out because ice took Down the lines, Danny. His breathing was getting faster and shallower and his nostrils were flaring with each breath. I recognised this from hospital trips. Respiratory distress. I did more chest therapy and tried the inhaler again and nothing worked. Danny's lips were turning blue at the edges. He was using muscles in his neck and stomach just to breathe. His whole body working for every bit of air. He looked at me with scared eyes and said, I can't get air. I tried every phone again and got nothing. I ran outside and banged on neighbour's doors, but no one was home or they couldn't help. Danny was sitting straight up because he couldn't breathe, lying down, wheezing with every exhale. His fingernails were turning blue. He was too tired to cough anymore, which was worse. He said, am I gonna die? And I told him no, I wasn't going to let that happen. I looked out the window at Mister Leroy's truck with chains on the tires just sitting in his driveway. Mister Leroy was at his daughter's house riding out the storm. I wrapped Danny in a blanket and carried him outside. He weighed almost nothing because C F. Always kept him small. My feet slipped on the icy steps and I went down hard on one knee. But I didn't drop him. The truck door was unlocked and I put Danny in the passenger seat and buckled him in. His head lolled to the side and The whistling sound he made with each breath was get and quieter. Keys in the visor, like always. I'd never driven, but I'd watched my parents a thousand times. I turned the key and stalled. It started again. Stalled again. Third time. I gave it more gas and the truck lurched backward and I slammed the brakes and we skidded sideways across the driveway. I got it into drive and the back end fishtailed so hard I thought we were going in the ditch. Truck shot forward, tyres spinning on ice before they caught. I couldn't see through the freezing rain, so I hunched over the wheel and squinted at the road. The truck slid through the first intersection and I just held on and prayed. Danny's breathing was barely audible now. I pushed the gas harder. We hit black ice on Miller Road and spun completely around. I was screaming as the world whipped past the windows, headlights swinging across trees and mailboxes. When we stopped, we were somehow still on the road, facing the right direction. I kept driving. I blew through a red light because no one else was stupid enough to be out. The truck fishtailed on the hill by the church and sideswiped a parked car. I heard metal scraping and didn't stop. voice_to_text: I asked to hold my baby, and the doctor told me to shut up. I've been pregnant for 41 weeks. The doctors kept saying, any day now for three weeks straight while I waddled around like a penguin. My husband works in the medical field, so I let him handle all the hospital stuff. So when he finally scheduled a date to get this baby out, I cried happy tears. My husband held my face and said, we're finally gonna meet our daughter. He's been reading parenting books. It's month two of this pregnancy, and recently took to practicing swaddling on our cat. I've never wanted anything more than to hold this baby, to finally meet the little person who's been kicking my ribs for months. The moment I walked into the section of the hospital titled Labour and delivery, something felt wrong. The intake nurse didn't even look up from her computer when I approached. Name. She snapped. I told her. She sighed like I was ruining her day. You're early. I wasn't early. I was exactly on time. She pointed down the hall. Room 4. Change into the gown on the bed. Someone will deal with you. Eventually kept telling myself it was fine, that my husband would be here soon. I texted him, just got to my room. His response made my stomach drop. Don't freak out, but I got rear ended really bad on the highway. I'm fine, but the car is totaled. Coming as fast As I can. I stared at my phone, alone in that cold room, trying not to panic. A nurse came in without knocking. She grabbed my arm and started inserting an I V. Wait, I said. My husband isn't here yet. Can we just wait until he gets here before we start anything? She didn't even look at me. We're on a schedule. I watched her push something into the line. What is that? I asked. Pitocin. But I thought we were going to discuss the plan first. She glares at me and says, you want this baby out or not? She left before I could respond. Then my husband texted me. The police are making me stay until the tow truck clears the scene. It's going to be okay, though. I love you. Within 20 minutes, my contractions started hitting hard. I was gripping the bed rails, tears streaming down my face. I pressed the call button. A different nurse appeared in the doorway. I need ice chips. I managed. Please. She glanced at her clipboard. I'll get to it. She never came back. An hour later, I pressed the button again. Another nurse. I asked for ice chips an hour ago, and I need to talk to someone about pain management. He rolled her eyes. There's water right there, and the doctor will be in when he's ready. The doctor finally appeared two hours later. He checked the monitors, checked his watch, and started toward the door. Wait. I said, crying now. I'm in so much pain. Can we please talk about an epidural or something? He barely turned around. You're only at six centimetres. This is normal. First time. Mothers always think they know better than the medical professionals. He left. I had never felt so alone. I kept texting my husband, but the last message he sent was, phone is at 1%. I will be there. You're so strong. So none of my messages were going through. The pressure became unbearable, so I screamed. The doctor rushed back in, barking orders. Nurses appeared from nowhere. Push, he commanded. But my husband. I say, I don't care. Push! I pushed until I saw stars. Until I heard a tiny cry that made everything else disappear. My husband burst through the door, somehow looking worse than me. His shirt was torn. Face panicked. I'm here! I'm here! Our daughter was in the doctor's arms. Perfect. Screaming, alive. I reached out, exhausted, sobbing. Please, please, I whispered. Can I hold my baby? The doctor didn't look at me. We need to run tests first. Please, just for one second. He finally turned irritation all over his face. Ma'am, shut up and let us do our jobs. The room went dead silent. My husband stepped forward with a look I'd never seen before. What did you just say to my wife? The doctor straightened. Sir, you need to calm down or I will have security remove you. My husband laughed. Coldly remove me. Do you have any idea who I am? He pulled out his hospital I D. Badge. I sit on this hospital's medical board. I review misconduct cases. I decide who keeps their job here. The doctor's face went white. The nurse, who rolled her eyes, physically stepped backward. The rest of you better hope you treated my wife with more compassion than the man who told my wife to shut up after she just gave birth to our child. He looked at each person in the room. Because by Monday morning, I will have every single person who mistreated my wife suspended. The doctor placed our baby in my arms so gently, you'd think she was made of glass. The nurse, who disappeared for an hour, suddenly appeared with warm blankets, ice chips and extra pillows for me. Is there anything else you need? The nurse asked me. I looked at my husband, then at our daughter's perfect face. I told the nurse, yes, for you to get out.

video_description: üò≠üò≠@TheJubalShowJubalinthemorningradioprogram‚ÄúBrookeandJubal‚Äù#brookeandjubal#brookandjubalinthemorning#seconddate#seconddateupdate#prank
voice_to_text: I asked to hold my baby, and the doctor told me to shut up. I've been pregnant for 41 weeks. The doctors kept saying, any day now for three weeks straight while I waddled around like a penguin. My husband works in the medical field, so I let him handle all the hospital stuff. So when he finally scheduled a date to get this baby out, I cried happy tears. My husband held my face and said, we're finally gonna meet our daughter. He's been reading parenting books. It's month two of this pregnancy, and recently took to practicing swaddling on our cat. I've never wanted anything more than to hold this baby, to finally meet the little person who's been kicking my ribs for months. The moment I walked into the section of the hospital titled Labour and delivery, something felt wrong. The intake nurse didn't even look up from her computer when I approached. Name. She snapped. I told her. She sighed like I was ruining her day. You're early. I wasn't early. I was exactly on time. She pointed down the hall. Room 4. Change into the gown on the bed. Someone will deal with you. Eventually kept telling myself it was fine, that my husband would be here soon. I texted him, just got to my room. His response made my stomach drop. Don't freak out, but I got rear ended really bad on the highway. I'm fine, but the car is totaled. Coming as fast As I can. I stared at my phone, alone in that cold room, trying not to panic. A nurse came in without knocking. She grabbed my arm and started inserting an I V. Wait, I said. My husband isn't here yet. Can we just wait until he gets here before we start anything? She didn't even look at me. We're on a schedule. I watched her push something into the line. What is that? I asked. Pitocin. But I thought we were going to discuss the plan first. She glares at me and says, you want this baby out or not? She left before I could respond. Then my husband texted me. The police are making me stay until the tow truck clears the scene. It's going to be okay, though. I love you. Within 20 minutes, my contractions started hitting hard. I was gripping the bed rails, tears streaming down my face. I pressed the call button. A different nurse appeared in the doorway. I need ice chips. I managed. Please. She glanced at her clipboard. I'll get to it. She never came back. An hour later, I pressed the button again. Another nurse. I asked for ice chips an hour ago, and I need to talk to someone about pain management. He rolled her eyes. There's water right there, and the doctor will be in when he's ready. The doctor finally appeared two hours later. He checked the monitors, checked his watch, and started toward the door. Wait. I said, crying now. I'm in so much pain. Can we please talk about an epidural or something? He barely turned around. You're only at six centimetres. This is normal. First time. Mothers always think they know better than the medical professionals. He left. I had never felt so alone. I kept texting my husband, but the last message he sent was, phone is at 1%. I will be there. You're so strong. So none of my messages were going through. The pressure became unbearable, so I screamed. The doctor rushed back in, barking orders. Nurses appeared from nowhere. Push, he commanded. But my husband. I say, I don't care. Push! I pushed until I saw stars. Until I heard a tiny cry that made everything else disappear. My husband burst through the door, somehow looking worse than me. His shirt was torn. Face panicked. I'm here! I'm here! Our daughter was in the doctor's arms. Perfect. Screaming, alive. I reached out, exhausted, sobbing. Please, please, I whispered. Can I hold my baby? The doctor didn't look at me. We need to run tests first. Please, just for one second. He finally turned irritation all over his face. Ma'am, shut up and let us do our jobs. The room went dead silent. My husband stepped forward with a look I'd never seen before. What did you just say to my wife? The doctor straightened. Sir, you need to calm down or I will have security remove you. My husband laughed. Coldly remove me. Do you have any idea who I am? He pulled out his hospital I D. Badge. I sit on this hospital's medical board. I review misconduct cases. I decide who keeps their job here. The doctor's face went white. The nurse, who rolled her eyes, physically stepped backward. The rest of you better hope you treated my wife with more compassion than the man who told my wife to shut up after she just gave birth to our child. He looked at each person in the room. Because by Monday morning, I will have every single person who mistreated my wife suspended. The doctor placed our baby in my arms so gently, you'd think she was made of glass. The nurse, who disappeared for an hour, suddenly appeared with warm blankets, ice chips and extra pillows for me. Is there anything else you need? The nurse asked me. I looked at my husband, then at our daughter's perfect face. I told the nurse, yes, for you to get out.

video_description: üò≠üò≠@TheJubalShowJubalinthemorningradioprogram‚ÄúBrookeandJubal‚Äù#brookeandjubal#brookandjubalinthemorning#seconddate#seconddateupdate#prank
voice_to_text: when was doing the wrong thing the right choice I was 12 years old and home alone with my little brother during the worst ice storm in 20 years Danny was 7 and had cystic fibrosis been managing it his whole life I knew the routine better than my own homework chest physiotherapy twice a day to loosen the mucus nebulizer treatments morning and night enzyme pills with every meal and always watch for signs of infection parents went to Grandma's 90th birthday two hours away and I told them I could handle it because I've done it 100 times before the storm hit harder than expected and the power went out around six PM but Danny had already done his evening nebulizer so we just lit some candles and played cards and listened to the ice hitting the windows around eight PM he started coughing more than usual I did chest percussion like they taught me pounding on his back to loosen everything up and he coughed a bunch of stuff up and seemed better by nine PM the coughing was worse deep and wet and Danny said his chest felt tight I gave him his rescue inhaler two puffs like the doctor showed us and waited he still couldn't catch his breath between coughing fits I tried to call our parents but my cell was dead towers overloaded from the storm I tried 9 1 1 and got nothing but static the landline was out because ice took down the lines Danny his breathing was getting faster and shallower and his nostrils were flaring with each breath I recognised this from hospital trips respiratory distress I did more chest therapy and tried the inhaler again and nothing worked Danny's lips were turning blue at the edges he was using muscles in his neck and stomach just to breathe his whole body working for every bit of air he looked at me with scared eyes and said I can't get air I tried every phone again and got nothing I ran outside and banged on neighbour's doors but no one was home or they couldn't help Danny was sitting straight up because he couldn't breathe lying down wheezing with every exhale his fingernails were turning blue he was too tired to cough anymore which was worse he said am I gonna die and I told him no I wasn't going to let that happen I looked out the window at Mister Leroy's truck with chains on the tires just sitting in his driveway Mister Leroy was at his daughter's house riding out the storm I wrapped Danny in a blanket and carried him outside he weighed almost nothing because C F always kept him small my feet slipped on the icy steps and I went down hard on one knee but I didn't drop him the truck door was unlocked and I put Danny in the passenger seat and buckled him in his head lolled to the side and the whistling sound he made with each breath was get and quieter keys in the visor like always I'd never driven but I'd watched my parents a thousand times I turned the key and stalled it started again stalled again third time I gave it more gas and the truck lurched backward and I slammed the brakes and we skidded sideways across the driveway I got it into drive and the back end fishtailed so hard I thought we were going in the ditch truck shot forward tyres spinning on ice before they caught I couldn't see through the freezing rain so I hunched over the wheel and squinted at the road the truck slid through the first intersection and I just held on and prayed Danny's breathing was barely audible now I pushed the gas harder we hit black ice on Miller Road and spun completely around I was screaming as the world whipped past the windows headlights swinging across trees and mailboxes when we stopped we were somehow still on the road facing the right direction I kept driving I blew through a red light because no one else was stupid enough to be out the truck fishtailed on the hill by the church and sideswiped a parked car I heard metal scraping and didn't stop the hospital was 15 minutes away in good weather I made it in eight I pulled up to the emergency entrance going way too fast and slammed the brakes and the truck jumped a curb and stopped half on the sidewalk I laid on the horn until people came running I was screaming that my brother had C F and couldn't breathe they put him on a stretcher and someone put an oxygen mask on his face and they ran him inside a nurse found me on the waiting room floor in wet pajamas no shoes shaking so hard my teeth were chattering she brought me a blanket and told me I did good my parents arrived three hours later hysterical the doctor said Danny was stable his oxygen levels were when he came in and another hour could have caused organ damage or worse a cop showed up the next day about the stolen truck and the car I hit I told him everything Mister Leroy visited Danny in the hospital and heard the whole story he shook my hand and told the cop there was nothing to press charges for he said that's not stealing that's being a brother Danny's 20 now and doing fine Mister Leroy taught me to drive for real the summer I turned 15

video_description: üò≠üò≠@TheJubalShowJubalinthemorningradioprogram‚ÄúBrookeandJubal‚Äù#brookeandjubal#brookandjubalinthemorning#seconddate#seconddateupdate#prank
voice_to_text: My sister threw a wine glass and had a screaming meltdown at Thanksgiving because I didn't tell her about my pregnancy before announcing it to the whole family. So I announced her biggest secret. Me and my husband Oliver found out I was pregnant in early October after trying for two years. We were so excited, but also terrified because I'd had an early miscarriage the year before that devastated us. My doctor said everything looked good, but recommended waiting until after 12 weeks to tell people just to be safe. We decided Thanksgiving would be perfect since the whole family would be together and we'd be at 14 weeks by then. I only told my brother Leo and my cousin Amy because they both knew about the miscarriage and kept checking on me. They promised not to tell anyone and actually kept their word. My sister Gina is 34 and has four kids and thinks that makes her the pregnancy expert of the family. She called me the week before Thanksgiving asking if I had any news to share. I said no, just looking forward to seeing everyone. She said I seemed different lately and wondered if something was going on. I changed the subject to her kids, and she let it go, but I could tell she was suspicious. The thing about Gina is she literally cannot keep information to herself. When I got into my master's program, I told her first because I was so excited and Wanted to share with my sister. She called her mom an hour later and announced it before I could. When Oliver proposed, I called her, crying happy tears, and she immediately posted about it online, tagging our entire family before I could tell anyone myself. When I got promoted at work, she told everyone at Sunday dinner before I arrived. She. She always says she's just so excited for me, she can't help herself. But it's really about her being the one with information to share. So this time, Oliver and I agreed we wouldn't tell her until we told everyone. Thanksgiving came, and after dinner, I stood up and said we had an announcement. I told everyone we were expecting and due in may. Everyone started cheering and hugging us, except Gina, who just stared at me. Then she started crying. Not happy tears, but angry tears. She asked how long I'd known, and I said about six weeks. She lost it. She stood up and yelled that I was supposed to tell her first. She said she told me about all four of her pregnancies before anyone else, and I'd betrayed her by not doing the same. She said sisters were supposed to share everything, and I'd made her look stupid. My mom tried to calm her down, but Gina turned on her and asked if she knew. When my mom said no, Gina asked who did know. Amy and Leo stayed quiet, but Gina figured it out. And started screaming at them, too, for keeping secrets. She. She said the whole family was against her and treating her like she couldn't be trusted. My dad told her to calm down and be happy for me, but she said, how could she be happy when I deliberately excluded her from the most important news? She said I'd ruined our relationship and she'd never forgive me for making her the last to know. Then she went after Oliver, saying he turned me against my own sister. Oliver said we just wanted to wait until we were sure everything was okay. Gina said that was stupid because she would have supported me either way, and now she felt like I didn't consider her real family. She actually said the words, real family tells each other everything immediately. The irony was incredible, coming from someone who spoiled every important moment I'd ever had. My brother Leo finally spoke up and said, maybe if Gina could keep her mouth shut for once, people would tell her things. Gina threw her wine glass at the wall, and it shattered everywhere. My four year old nephew started crying. My mom started crying. Gina's husband Jake tried to get her to leave, but she refused. She said she wasn't going anywhere until I apologised for humiliating her. I said I wasn't apologizing for protecting my own announcement. She said I was a terrible sister and she was done with me. She told her kids to Get their coats and started packing up the dishes she brought. While she was dramatically shoving Tupperware into bags. I stood up and said, if we were sharing everything like real family, then everyone should know that Gina had been texting her ex boyfriend Ryan for the past six months. Jake froze. Gina went white. Full story on channel link.

voice_to_text: I rescued my brother's dog and now he wants me to pay him. My brother Perry has always collected things he couldn't take care of. Cars rusting in his yard, tools he never used. And for a few terrible years, animals. It started with a cat he saw at a shelter and just had to have. Then another cat, then a dog, then three more dogs. Then, for some reason, a goat. He'd get so excited bringing them home, posting pictures online, telling everyone what a great rescue dad he was. Then he'd get bored. The dogs ended up chained outside in all weather. The cats lived in filthy cages in his garage. I don't even know what happened to the goat. I begged him to let me help. I said I'd come over and feed them, walk them, anything. He told me to mind my own business. They're fine. Animals are tougher than you think. Animal control got called twice by his neighbours. Both times he cleaned up just enough to pass inspection, then went right back to neglecting them. I started sneaking over when he was at work, just to give them food and water. I'd sit with the dogs for a few minutes, let them remember what it felt like to be touched by someone who wasn't screaming at them. One winter, I came over and found a German Shepherd puppy shivering in a broken plastic crate with no food, no water, and sores all over her. Legs from lying in her own waste. She was maybe five months old, and she looked at me with these huge, huge, terrified eyes. And I just couldn't leave her there. I put her in my car and drove away. I called Perry from my driveway and told him I was keeping the dog and he could call the cops if he wanted. He laughed. Take her. She's defective anyway. Wouldn't stop crying. I took the other animals, too. Over the next few months. Every time I asked, he said yes because he was bored of them by then. I rehomed the cats and the other dogs to people I trusted. But I kept a German Shepherd. I named her fluffer nut because she had this ridiculous, fluffy tail that didn't match the rest of her body. She was terrified of everything at first. Loud noises, sudden movements, men, other dogs, the vacuum, the T V, her own shadow. I spent months just sitting on the floor with her, letting her come to me, teaching her that not every hand was going to hurt her. Slowly, she started to trust me. And once she did, I realised what an incredible dog she was. Smart, athletic, eager to learn, beautiful. A friend of mine who does dog shows watched her run in my backyard one day and said, you know she could compete, right? I laughed it off at first, but Fluffer Nut loved training. She loved having a job. So I started entering her in local shows just for fun. Fluffer Nut won best in show at nationals last month. 50 thousand dollar prize. It was the best day of my life. I was ugly, crying while they put the ribbon on her. And she just stood there looking perfect, tail wagging like she'd always known she would. The champion. The local news picked up the story, rescue dog wins big with a photo of me and fluffernut and her trophy. I didn't think anything of it until Perry showed up at my house the next day. He walked right up to my porch and said, that's my dog. I want the prize money. I laughed in his face. He didn't laugh back. I'm serious. I have the original adoption paperwork from the shelter. You stole my property, I said. You told me to take her. You called her defective. He shrugged. I was joking. I never officially signed her over to you. I said. You left her outside in December with no food. She had frostbite on her ears when I took her to the vet. I have the records, he said. That doesn't matter. Legally, she's still mine. I said. I have three years of vet bills, training receipts and registration papers in my name. You have a piece of paper from the shelter you probably can't even find. He stepped closer. I'll sue you. I smiled. Do it. I'd love to show a judge the photos. I Took when I rescued her. I documented everything, Perry. Every sore on her body, every rib showing through her skin. Every day she went without water. I have time stamps. He went quiet. I said, you threw her away like garbage. You didn't train her. You didn't love her. You didn't even feed her. I'm the one who turned her into a champion. You don't get to show up now and pretend you had anything to do with this. He said, you owe me. I'm the reason you even have that dog. I said, get off my property and don't ever contact me about my dog again. He stood there for a second like he was thinking about arguing, then turned and walked back to his car. Fluffer nut sat at my feet the whole time, calm as anything, watching him go. He tried to sue anyway. The judge dismissed it in 20 minutes.

video_description: üò≠üò≠@TheJubalShowJubalinthemorningradioprogram‚ÄúBrookeandJubal‚Äù#brookeandjubal#brookandjubalinthemorning#seconddate#seconddateupdate#prank
voice_to_text: I purposefully order meat items so I don't have to share with my vegetarian friend. My friend Hazel and I have been going out to eat together for almost two years, and somewhere along the way she decided that her being vegetarian means she gets to eat my food, but I can never eat hers. It started small at first she ask for a bite of my burger or steal a few of my fries, but over time it escalated to the point where she basically plans her entire order around splitting mine. The thing is, I love sharing food with people. I'm the person who orders three appetizers so everyone can try everything. But with Hazel it's different because it's completely one sided. She'll order a seven dollar side salad, then eat half of my eighteen dollar entree and act like she's doing me a favour by keeping me company while I eat. I've tried bringing it up casually like hey, wanna split an appetizer? And she always says, oh no, I'm vegetarian. I can't eat most of those things. But the second my food arrives, her fork is already on my plate. Two months ago we went to a diner and she ordered oatmeal and fruit for six dollars. I got a full breakfast platter with eggs, bacon and pancakes for $14. She ate three of my pancakes, half my bacon and didn't even ask. Last month we went to an Italian place and I ordered chicken Parmesan She ordered minestrone soup and a small Caesar salad. The moment my plate hit the table, she said, oh, that looks amazing. Can I try some? I said, sure, thinking she meant one bite. She ate four full pieces of my chicken, taking all the cheese and sauce with it. When I suggested we split her soup, she laughed and said, oh, this is vegetarian. You wouldn't like it. There's no protein in here. I was fuming, but I didn't say anything because I hate confrontation. And honestly, I didn't wanna make things weird. So I came up with a new strategy. Order only meat heavy dishes that she physically cannot share. Last week we went to this Mexican restaurant that we go to all the time. Usually I'd order something we could both enjoy, but not this time. I was genuinely craving nachos, but I knew if I ordered the regular ones, she'd demolish half of them while I walk.

She stood in my living room crying fake tears, saying I was killing him by keeping organs I didn't deserve. You have two healthy kidneys and Tyler has none. You could save him today if you weren't so heartless. Tyler destroyed his kidneys drinking a bottle of vodka everyday for 15 years. Started at 16, never stopped. Mom bought him his first bottle. Said boys needed to learn to handle liquor. When doctors warned him at 25 that his kidneys were failing, mom said they were being dramatic. When he needed his first dialysis at 30, she blamed the doctors for not trying harder. Now, at 32, both kidneys were dead. He needed a transplant or he'd die within a year. Mom's kidney wasn't a match. Dad's wasn't either. But mine were perfect. One kidney. I told her the first time she asked. I'll give him one. One isn't enough, she said. His body is weak. He needs both to have a real chance. Then I'd need dialysis forever. I'm 28. That's 50 years of machines keeping me alive. You're stronger than Tyler. You can handle it. This was classic mom. Tyler was her golden boy since birth. He got a car at 16. I got nothing. He got college paid for, but dropped out. I got student loans. He got Bailed out of jail three times. I got kicked out at 18 for getting pregnant. That pregnancy ended in miscarriage, but mom said I deserved it for being irresponsible. I became a nurse anyway. Worked three jobs to pay for school. Built a life without any help from the family that forgot I existed. Until they needed something. For 10 years, mom never called. Neither did Tyler. I found out about family events through Facebook. Wasn't invited to Tyler's wedding, Mom's 60th birthday, or Dad's retirement party. But now they needed my organs. So suddenly, I was family again. The harassment started after I said no. Mom called my work, told them I was having a mental breakdown. Called my landlord, said I was unstable. Called my boyfriend, told him I was a murderer who would let my own brother die. She showed up at my hospital during my shift. Everyone, look at the nurse who won't save her brother's life. She has two kidneys and won't share. Security escorted her out, but she came back the next day. And the next three weeks. She stalked me. Calling, texting, showing up everywhere. Tyler's dying because of you. You're selfish. What kind of sister watches her brother die? What she didn't know was that Tyler wasn't dying. Not really. He was on dialysis three times a week. Uncomfortable, but manageable. Could live for decades like that. I knew because I worked in the dialysis unit. Saw patients in their 70s who'd Been on machines for 20 years. Tyler just didn't want the inconvenience. Neither did mom. She wanted her perfect son back, not one attached to machines. So she decided I should be the one attached to machines instead. I finally called Tyler directly. Hadn't spoken to him in two years. Do you know Mom's demanding both kidneys? I asked. Yeah. He said so. So I'd be on dialysis forever. You understand that, right? You're younger. You'd adapt better. Plus, you don't have kids to worry about. Neither do you. But I might someday. You already tried and couldn't. He actually said that? Referenced my miscarriage like it was proof I didn't deserve working organs. That's when I decided to end this completely. I scheduled a meeting with Tyler's transplant team. Told I'm about Mom's pressure. Show them her texts demanding both kidneys. The lead surgeon's face went dark. She wants you to donate both. That's not even legal. We'd never approve that. Turns out mom had been telling Tyler the team would do it if I agreed. Complete lie. The surgeon called mom and Tyler immediately. Full story on channel link below.

video_description: üò≠üò≠@TheJubalShowJubalinthemorningradioprogram‚ÄúBrookeandJubal‚Äù#brookeandjubal#brookandjubalinthemorning#seconddate#seconddateupdate#prank
voice_to_text: My sister threw a wine glass and had a screaming meltdown at Thanksgiving because I didn't tell her about my pregnancy before announcing it to the whole family. So I announced her biggest secret. Me and my husband Oliver found out I was pregnant in early October after trying for two years. We were so excited, but also terrified because I'd had an early miscarriage the year before that devastated us. My doctor said everything looked good, but recommended waiting until after 12 weeks to tell people just to be safe. We decided Thanksgiving would be perfect since the whole family would be together and we'd be at 14 weeks by then. I only told my brother Leo and my cousin Amy because they both knew about the miscarriage and kept checking on me. They promised not to tell anyone and actually kept their word. My sister Gina is 34 and has four kids and thinks that makes her the pregnancy expert of the family. She called me the week before Thanksgiving asking if I had any news to share. I said no, just looking forward to seeing everyone. She said I seemed different lately and wondered if something was going on. I changed the subject to her kids, and she let it go, but I could tell she was suspicious. The thing about Gina is she literally cannot keep information to herself. When I got into my master's program, I told her first because I was so excited and Wanted to share with my sister. She called her mom an hour later and announced it before I could. When Oliver proposed, I called her, crying happy tears, and she immediately posted about it online, tagging our entire family before I could tell anyone myself. When I got promoted at work, she told everyone at Sunday dinner before I arrived. She. She always says she's just so excited for me, she can't help herself. But it's really about her being the one with information to share. So this time, Oliver and I agreed we wouldn't tell her until we told everyone. Thanksgiving came, and after dinner, I stood up and said we had an announcement. I told everyone we were expecting and due in may. Everyone started cheering and hugging us, except Gina, who just stared at me. Then she started crying. Not happy tears, but angry tears. She asked how long I'd known, and I said about six weeks. She lost it. She stood up and yelled that I was supposed to tell her first. She said she told me about all four of her pregnancies before anyone else, and I'd betrayed her by not doing the same. She said sisters were supposed to share everything, and I'd made her look stupid. My mom tried to calm her down, but Gina turned on her and asked if she knew. When my mom said no, Gina asked who did know. Amy and Leo stayed quiet, but Gina figured it out. And started screaming at them, too, for keeping secrets. She. She said the whole family was against her and treating her like she couldn't be trusted. My dad told her to calm down and be happy for me, but she said, how could she be happy when I deliberately excluded her from the most important news? She said I'd ruined our relationship and she'd never forgive me for making her the last to know. Then she went after Oliver, saying he turned me against my own sister. Oliver said we just wanted to wait until we were sure everything was okay. Gina said that was stupid because she would have supported me either way, and now she felt like I didn't consider her real family. She actually said the words, real family tells each other everything immediately. The irony was incredible, coming from someone who spoiled every important moment I'd ever had. My brother Leo finally spoke up and said, maybe if Gina could keep her mouth shut for once, people would tell her things. Gina threw her wine glass at the wall, and it shattered everywhere. My four year old nephew started crying. My mom started crying. Gina's husband Jake tried to get her to leave, but she refused. She said she wasn't going anywhere until I apologised for humiliating her. I said I wasn't apologizing for protecting my own announcement. She said I was a terrible sister and she was done with me. She told her kids to Get their coats and started packing up the dishes she brought. While she was dramatically shoving Tupperware into bags. I stood up and said, if we were sharing everything like real family, then everyone should know that Gina had been texting her ex boyfriend Ryan for the past six months. Jake froze. Gina went white. Full story on channel link.

voice_to_text: My mother demands I give both my kidneys to my golden child brother. My mother called me selfish for refusing to give both my kidneys to my brother Tyler. Said boys needed to learn to handle liquor. When doctors warned him at 25 that his kidneys were failing, mom said they were being dramatic. When he needed his first dialysis at 30, she blamed the doctors for not trying harder. Now, at 32, both kidneys were dead. He needed a transplant or he'd die within a year. Mom's kidney wasn't a match. Dad's wasn't either. But mine were perfect. One kidney. I told her the first time she asked. I'll give him one. One isn't enough, she said. His body is weak. He needs both to have a real chance. Then I'd need dialysis forever. I'm 28. That's 50 years of machines keeping me alive. You're stronger than Tyler. You can handle it. This was classic mom. Tyler was her golden boy since birth. He got a car at 16. I got nothing. He got college paid for, but dropped out. I got student loans. He got Bailed out of jail three times. I got kicked out at 18 for getting pregnant. That pregnancy ended in miscarriage, but mom said I deserved it for being irresponsible. I became a nurse anyway. Worked three jobs to pay for school. Built a life without any help from the family that forgot I existed. Until they needed something. For 10 years, mom never called. Neither did Tyler. I found out about family events through Facebook. Wasn't invited to Tyler's wedding, Mom's 60th birthday, or Dad's retirement party. But now they needed my organs. So suddenly, I was family again. The harassment started after I said no. Mom called my work, told them I was having a mental breakdown. Called my landlord, said I was unstable. Called my boyfriend, told him I was a murderer who would let my own brother die. Security escorted her out, but she came back the next day. And the next three weeks. She stalked me. Calling, texting, showing up everywhere. Tyler's dying because of you. You're selfish. What kind of sister watches her brother die? What she didn't know was that Tyler wasn't dying. Not really. He was on dialysis three times a week. Uncomfortable, but manageable. Plus, you don't have kids to worry about. Neither do you. But I might someday. You already tried and couldn't. He actually said that? Referenced my miscarriage like it was proof I didn't deserve working organs. That's when I decided to end this completely. I scheduled a meeting with Tyler's transplant team. Told I'm about Mom's pressure. Show them her texts demanding both kidneys. The lead surgeon's face went dark. She wants you to donate both. That's not even legal. We'd never approve that. Turns out mom had been telling Tyler the team would do it if I agreed. Complete lie. The surgeon called mom and Tyler immediately. Full story on channel link below.

I only told my brother Leo and my cousin Amy because they both knew about the miscarriage and kept checking on me. They promised not to tell anyone and actually kept their word. video_description: üò≠üò≠@TheJubalShowJubalinthemorningradioprogram‚ÄúBrookeandJubal‚Äù#brookeandjubal#brookandjubalinthemorning#seconddate#seconddateupdate#prank
voice_to_text: My sister sent me a wedding invitation that said no hard feelings right at the bottom. She married my ex fiance six months after I caught them in bed together. I was not gonna let this one slide. The wedding was in 48 hours when my mom called, frantic. Your sister collapsed at her dress fitting. They rushed her to the hospital. What happened? They don't know yet. She's getting tests. Can you come to the hospital right now? I dropped everything and drove straight there. My hands shook on the wheel. Rochelle and I hadn't spoken in 18 months. Not since I found her with Devon. But she was still my sister. I ran through the parking lot, called my dad while sprinting. What room? Fourth floor, 4:20. Hurry! The elevator took forever. I took the stairs two at a time, burst through the door, ran down the hallway. I pushed inside, breathing hard. Rochelle sat up in bed, pale. My parents flanked her. Devon held her hand. What happened? Is she okay? My mom's face crumpled. They found something. Thyroid cancer, Rochelle said quietly. Stage two. The room spun. I grabbed the door frame. They found it during blood work on her yearly check up. Dad explained. She's been tired, losing weight. We thought it was wedding stress. When did you find out? I asked. Four months ago, Rochelle whispered. I didn't want anyone to worry. I wanted one normal thing before everything became about being sick. Devon Squeezed her hand. That's why we moved the wedding up. She starts treatment next month. The doctors say with treatment she has good odds, mom added. But the next year will be brutal. Radiation, possible surgery. Rochelle looked at me. I'm sorry I uninvited you. I was scared you'd ruin your wedding. Yeah, I was planning to. My mom gasped. What? I called the venue pretending to be Rochelle and changed details. I told the caterer there were peanut allergy. I sent the bridesmaids the wrong dresses. I told Devon's groomsmen the wrong bachelor party location. Rochelle went white. No wonder everything's falling apart. Every vendor called this week and said confusion about Times, Menus, locations. I thought we were dealing with incompetent people. It was me. I said all of it. I wanted to destroy your wedding because I was angry. I couldn't finish. The weight crushed me. The caterer quit yesterday, mom said quietly. The photographer almost failed. Three bridesmaids bought the wrong dresses and can't get the right ones in time. Michelle started crying. I just want had one perfect day before my life becomes hospitals and chemo and maybe dying. You're not going to die, Devon said firmly. You don't know that. And now my wedding is ruined because my sister hates me. I don't hate you, I said, but my actions said otherwise. The wedding is in 48 hours, dad said, looking at me. Can you fix this? I spent the next 48 hours fixing Everything. Venue, caterer, dresses, photographer. By Saturday, it was perfect. The bridal suite. I told Rochelle. I fixed everything. Your wedding will be perfect. Why? She asked, after everything I did these past few months? Because I saw your medical records. You had a consultation six months ago before Devin. You already suspected something was wrong. She went. Still, he was cheating on you, she whispered. I found out six months ago. He wouldn't stop, so I slept with him to force you to leave. With my diagnosis, I figured I wouldn't be around long enough for you to hate me forever. But then you fell in love with him. I said, no. No, I'm marrying him because dying alone terrifies me. Devin appeared. It's your turn now. Tell her the truth, Rochelle said. He looked at the floor. I cheated on you more than 10 times. But when Rochelle got sick, I changed. I showed up to every appointment, every test. I actually fell in love with her. I didn't plan to fall in love, Rochelle cried. I just wanted to save you from making the biggest mistake of your life. My sister had betrayed me to save me. My ex had changed, and I'd almost destroyed their wedding out of spite. You're getting married today, I said. And, Rochelle, you're beating this cancer. I'm going to every single chemo appointment, whether do you want me or not. We hugged and cried. The makeup artist sighed. I need another 30 minutes. The wedding was perfect. When they asked if anyone objected, I stood. Everyone gasped. I, I object to how they got together, I said, but I support where they ended up. It got a laugh from everyone, even from them. Three years later, at her daughter Hope's baptism, Michelle pulled me aside. I left those medical records out on purpose. I knew you'd read them and figure it out. I was too scared to just tell you. She manipulated me into forgiving her. And it worked.

video_description: üò≠üò≠@TheJubalShowJubalinthemorningradioprogram‚ÄúBrookeandJubal‚Äù#brookeandjubal#brookandjubalinthemorning#seconddate#seconddateupdate#prank
voice_to_text: My sister threw a wine glass and had a screaming meltdown at Thanksgiving because I didn't tell her about my pregnancy before announcing it to the whole family. So I announced her biggest secret. Me and my husband Oliver found out I was pregnant in early October after trying for two years. We were so excited, but also terrified because I'd had an early miscarriage the year before that devastated us. My doctor said everything looked good, but recommended waiting until after 12 weeks to tell people just to be safe. We decided Thanksgiving would be perfect since the whole family would be together and we'd be at 14 weeks by then. I only told my brother Leo and my cousin Amy because they both knew about the miscarriage and kept checking on me. They promised not to tell anyone and actually kept their word. My sister Gina is 34 and has four kids and thinks that makes her the pregnancy expert of the family. She called me the week before Thanksgiving asking if I had any news to share. I said no, just looking forward to seeing everyone. She said I seemed different lately and wondered if something was going on. I changed the subject to her kids, and she let it go, but I could tell she was suspicious. The thing about Gina is she literally cannot keep information to herself. When I got into my master's program, I told her first because I was so excited and Wanted to share with my sister. She called her mom an hour later and announced it before I could. When Oliver proposed, I called her, crying happy tears, and she immediately posted about it online, tagging our entire family before I could tell anyone myself. When I got promoted at work, she told everyone at Sunday dinner before I arrived. She. She always says she's just so excited for me, she can't help herself. But it's really about her being the one with information to share. So this time, Oliver and I agreed we wouldn't tell her until we told everyone. Thanksgiving came, and after dinner, I stood up and said we had an announcement. I told everyone we were expecting and due in may. Everyone started cheering and hugging us, except Gina, who just stared at me. Then she started crying. Not happy tears, but angry tears. She asked how long I'd known, and I said about six weeks. She lost it. She stood up and yelled that I was supposed to tell her first. She said she told me about all four of her pregnancies before anyone else, and I'd betrayed her by not doing the same. She said sisters were supposed to share everything, and I'd made her look stupid. My mom tried to calm her down, but Gina turned on her and asked if she knew. When my mom said no, Gina asked who did know. Amy and Leo stayed quiet, but Gina figured it out. And started screaming at them, too, for keeping secrets. She. She said the whole family was against her and treating her like she couldn't be trusted. My dad told her to calm down and be happy for me, but she said, how could she be happy when I deliberately excluded her from the most important news? She said I'd ruined our relationship and she'd never forgive me for making her the last to know. Then she went after Oliver, saying he turned me against my own sister. Oliver said we just wanted to wait until we were sure everything was okay. Gina said that was stupid because she would have supported me either way, and now she felt like I didn't consider her real family. She actually said the words, real family tells each other everything immediately. The irony was incredible, coming from someone who spoiled every important moment I'd ever had. My brother Leo finally spoke up and said, maybe if Gina could keep her mouth shut for once, people would tell her things. Gina threw her wine glass at the wall, and it shattered everywhere. My four year old nephew started crying. My mom started crying. Gina's husband Jake tried to get her to leave, but she refused. She said she wasn't going anywhere until I apologised for humiliating her. I said I wasn't apologizing for protecting my own announcement. She said I was a terrible sister and she was done with me. She told her kids to Get their coats and started packing up the dishes she brought. While she was dramatically shoving Tupperware into bags. I stood up and said, if we were sharing everything like real family, then everyone should know that Gina had been texting her ex boyfriend Ryan for the past six months. Jake froze. Gina went white. Full story on channel link.

video_description: üò≠üò≠@TheJubalShowJubalinthemorningradioprogram‚ÄúBrookeandJubal‚Äù#brookeandjubal#brookandjubalinthemorning#seconddate#seconddateupdate#prank
voice_to_text: I rescued my brother's dog and now he wants me to pay him. My brother Perry has always collected things he couldn't take care of. Cars rusting in his yard, tools he never used. And for a few terrible years, animals. It started with a cat he saw at a shelter and just had to have. Then another cat, then a dog, then three more dogs. Then, for some reason, a goat. He'd get so excited bringing them home, posting pictures online, telling everyone what a great rescue dad he was. Then he'd get bored. The dogs ended up chained outside in all weather. The cats lived in filthy cages in his garage. I don't even know what happened to the goat. I begged him to let me help. I said I'd come over and feed them, walk them, anything. He told me to mind my own business. They're fine. Animals are tougher than you think. Animal control got called twice by his neighbours. Both times he cleaned up just enough to pass inspection, then went right back to neglecting them. I started sneaking over when he was at work, just to give them food and water. I'd sit with the dogs for a few minutes, let them remember what it felt like to be touched by someone who wasn't screaming at them. One winter, I came over and found a German Shepherd puppy shivering in a broken plastic crate with no food, no water, and sores all over her. Legs from lying in her own waste. She was maybe five months old, and she looked at me with these huge, huge, terrified eyes. And I just couldn't leave her there. I put her in my car and drove away. I called Perry from my driveway and told him I was keeping the dog and he could call the cops if he wanted. He laughed. Take her. She's defective anyway. Wouldn't stop crying. I took the other animals, too. Over the next few months. Every time I asked, he said yes because he was bored of them by then. I rehomed the cats and the other dogs to people I trusted. But I kept a German Shepherd. I named her fluffer nut because she had this ridiculous, fluffy tail that didn't match the rest of her body. She was terrified of everything at first. Loud noises, sudden movements, men, other dogs, the vacuum, the T V, her own shadow. voice_to_text: My sister sent me a wedding invitation that said no hard feelings right at the bottom. She married my ex fiance six months after I caught them in bed together.
